Confluence Image Effects Plugin uses a wrong MIME type ({{ImageFilterServlet.java:151}}): {code}response.setContentType("image/jpg");{code}

While the right MIME type is "image/jp{color:red}e{color}g", see [wikipedia|https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_media_type#Type_image] and the [rfc2046|https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc2046].

This leads to problems when using a reverse proxy that adds the following header to all requests: {code}
X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
{code}
(e.g. by using {{/etc/apache2/conf.d/security}} on debian: {{Header set X-Content-Type-Options: "nosniff"}}).

This leads to images that use decorations provided by the image effects plugin do not display in Internet Explorer (tested with IE 10).

If {{X-Content-Type-Options: "nosniff"}} is not set, IE will just ignore the wrong Content-Type and sniff it. Other browsers seem unaffected as they treat "image/jpg" as "image/jpeg".

Obviously a workaround is to stop adding the security headers, thus leaving your users open to Content Type sniffing attacks.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
